  Review: tmp/emergent_clock_paper2.tex

  TLDR: The paper is in strong shape structurally, and almost every closed-form computation I could check by hand is correct. But it has one
  load-bearing calibration failure — Part III states unconditional theorems (Sym^r functoriality for all r, Sato–Tate for Maass forms) whose
  proof chain contains a link the paper itself elsewhere admits is "corroboration, not the proof" — plus one flat internal contradiction in
  §Status, one genuine mathematical hole in the Sato–Tate corollary (even tetrahedral/octahedral Maass forms), a misattributed converse
  theorem, and a factor-of-4 algebra slip. Details, with line numbers, below.

  ---
  A. Critical issues

  A1. Part III over-claims relative to its own proof status (the big one).
  The chain is thm:cps-nice → thm:func → cor:func234 → cor:satotate, and every link is stated unconditionally. But:

  - The proof of Lemma lem:rankgap (line 1329) ends: "Machine-checked for the Dirichlet model; the same determinant-one lane balance for the
  general symmetric-power/twist fiber, corroborated through Sym^13." A proof that ends in corroboration is not a proof of the stated
  generality.
  - §Status (lines 2339–2341) says explicitly: "the general tensor family is not yet Lean-formalized, and the numerics are corroboration, not
  the proof."
  - Yet cor:func234 (line 2232) says "Symmetric-power functoriality … is thereby established for every r," with no conditional.

  Meanwhile Theorem thm:universal(b) (lines 2023–2028) does this right: it explicitly gates entireness/boundedness on the per-fiber cell
  closure, "proved for the harmonic and Dirichlet classes and reduced to that one per-fiber input otherwise." Part III is inconsistent with
  Part II's own gating. There are two unproven-in-general links: (i) the global carrier reflection K(1/x)=εx^κK(x) for the general tensor
  theta (Lean covers the local algebra and the Dirichlet global case; the general global case is numerics through Sym^13), and (ii) residual
  extinction (E4) for cuspidal twists — the Lean FocalResidualGeneral covers the 2×2 pencil algebra, but the identification of that pencil's
  DC direction with the actual constant mode of the actual theta built from the actual λ_n is not proven for general fibers.

  Fix (per the house calibration rule): name the input once — e.g. Hypothesis CC(r,σ) (per-fiber cell closure / residual extinction for the
  cuspidal tensor fiber) — state thm:cps-nice, thm:func, cor:func234, cor:satotate conditionally on it, and then state the unconditional
  content at its true strength (Lean-proved harmonic/Dirichlet classes; numerics through Sym^13, L(Δ×E₁₁), Maass Sym²). This costs nothing
  structurally — the abstract already frames it this way ("reduced to a single per-fiber cell-closure input") — and it removes the
  desk-reject trigger of claiming two famous open problems (Sym^r for Maass forms is open even after Newton–Thorne, which covers only
  holomorphic forms; Sato–Tate for Maass forms is open).

  A2. §Status directly contradicts §4 on the comb's origin.
  Line 2352–2353: "The emergent comb is the cutoff's edge kinematics (R²≈1)." But §sec:comb (lines 433–441) proves the opposite with two
  controls: "This oscillation is intrinsic to the orbital transform Ψ…, not the cutoff's edges… replacing the compact cutoff by a smooth
  edgeless window leaves the comb unchanged." This looks like stale text from the earlier window-edge interpretation. Same stale vocabulary
  survives in the appendix: "edge-clock law" (line 2477), "window-edge law" (line 2483). Fix: reword §Status to match §4 ("the comb is the
  transform's own deterministic clock; the window sets only its ν-spacing"), and rename "edge-clock" → "clock law" in the appendix.

  A3. Sato–Tate corollary: the exceptional-type exclusion has a hole.
  Line 2280–2281: "it is not of the exceptional tetrahedral/octahedral type, which is holomorphic (weight one)." Only odd
  tetrahedral/octahedral Artin representations give weight-one holomorphic forms. Even ones correspond (and by Langlands–Tunnell actually
  lift) to Maass forms with eigenvalue exactly 1/4. So "non-dihedral Maass" does not exclude all exceptional types. Fix: add the hypothesis t
  ≠ 0 (eigenvalue > 1/4) — Galois-type forms force λ = 1/4, so this cleanly excludes them — or exclude "of Galois type" explicitly.

  A4. Converse-theorem attribution is wrong for the twist range used.
  Theorem thm:cps (line 2089) is labeled "Cogdell–Piatetski-Shapiro 1994, Thm. 1" with twist range 1 ≤ m < n−1 (i.e., m ≤ n−2). The 1994 IHÉS
  paper twists up to n−1; the improvement to n−2 is CPS II (1999) — which your bibliography already contains inside \cite{CPS}. Since the
  paper's whole ledger uses m ≤ n−2 (m < r with n = r+1), cite the 1999 paper for the theorem, and double-check the exact conclusion there
  (cuspidality of Π itself vs. the quasi-automorphic variant, which in CPS II attaches to the ramification-restricted twisting sets — the
  paper's remark at line 2100 asserting full cuspidality should be verified against the actual statement).

  A5. "Galois-free" vs. global parameters — internal inconsistency.
  Prop prop:cps-cand(c) (lines 2125–2127) insists the construction "reads only the local parameter family, never a global φ_π, so it applies
  verbatim to Maass π." But thm:func's hypothesis is "Sym^r φ_π irreducible" — a global-parameter condition that does not exist for Maass
  forms — and the pole argument in its proof (lines 2213–2216) computes dim Hom(φ_τ^∨, Sym^r φ_π) of global objects. Fix: state the
  exceptional/generic dichotomy automorphically (dihedral ⟺ π ≅ π⊗η for quadratic η; tetrahedral/octahedral via the Kim–Shahidi Sym²/Sym³
  cuspidality criteria), and present the Hom computation as the motivating dictionary, with the actual load carried by entireness of the
  carrier readout (which is what the ledger uses anyway).

  A6. Central-character mismatch.
  Lemma lem:selfdual (line 1386) assumes trivial central character (det φ_{π,v} = 1), and cor:satotate correctly restricts to trivial ω. But
  cor:func234 (line 2222) claims "every cuspidal π." Trivializing ω by twisting is not always possible over ℚ. Either carry ω_π through the
  determinant ledger in lem:selfdual (the machinery is built for exactly this — the ledger already books (det φ_τ)^{r+1}), or restrict
  cor:func234 to trivial ω_π.

  A7. §sec:rankdiff quietly asserts equivariant BSD.
  Lines 817–819: "The left side is the order of vanishing at s=1 of L(E,Ad_g,s)." The proven content is the Artin-formalism rank identity;
  equating the algebraic multiplicity with the analytic vanishing order is equivariant-BSD-strength and unmarked in the main text (the
  tiering remark below it covers automorphy and the p-adic regulator, but not this bridge). Fix: "is, conjecturally (equivariant BSD), the
  order of vanishing…" or restructure so only the proven identity is asserted.

