  B. Mathematical corrections (local, checkable)

  B1. Factor of 4 in the arithmetic-transparency computation (§sec:fl, line 674).
  With disc_k = −4sin²(2kθ), sin(2kθ) = sinθ·U_{2k−1}(cosθ), and sin²θ = |D|/4n:
  disc_k/D = (−4sin²θ·U²)/D = (D/n)·U²/D = U_{2k−1}(cosθ)²/n, not /(4n). Sanity check at k=1: disc₁/D = 4cos²θ/n = t²/n² = (t/n)². The
  headline claim (a rational square) survives either way; fix the constant.

  B2. thm:A14, the uniqueness-of-expansion identification (lines 246–251).
  The "asymptotic expansion in a fixed scale is unique" argument needs care: the coefficients A_m^±(∓C²D) are not constants in the large
  parameter D — they depend on D through x = C²D. Uniqueness in the scale {D^{−(m+1+a/2)}} requires either fixing C and handling the second
  parameter explicitly, or (cleaner) identifying b_m(u) = c_m^±(u/2) directly by comparing the Taylor data of ψ_u with Altuğ's Def. A.6 —
  likely a short computation that removes the referee-baitable step entirely.

  B3. lem:residual(ii) (lines 1246–1251) packs the analytic content into an "i.e.".
  Equating the Riemann–Hecke constant mode R (the x→0 constant term of K) with lim A(N)/N is a partial-summation/Tauberian step, not a
  definition. Also, bounded warped primitive alone gives holomorphy on Re s > 0; entireness then needs the reflection. Spell out the two-line
  partial-summation lemma (A(N)=O(1) + g of bounded variation and rapid decay ⟹ K(x)=O(1) as x→0 ⟹ no pole in Re s>0; reflection handles the
  rest).

  B4. prop:52 proof (lines 274–296).
  The exponent N appears in the statement and conclusion but the proof never says what N indexes (profile derivatives? expansion order?). The
  bookkeeping producing (lf²/√X)^{N−M+3} is asserted, not carried out. Either do it or mark the proof as a reduction sketch with a pointer
  to where each power arises.

  B5. Two competing boundedness routes — pick one.
  prop:niceness(B) and §Status (line 2315) use warped-Abel polynomial growth + Phragmén–Lindelöf; lem:bounded (lines 1463–1480) and
  thm:cps-nice (line 2167) prove genuine boundedness directly from the reflected integral, "no Phragmén–Lindelöf." The direct route is
  stronger (CPS wants bounded, not polynomial) and simpler. Make it primary everywhere and demote P–L to a remark; right now the paper argues
  with itself.

  B6. Does Poisson enter or not?
  §machinery (lines 1076–1087) derives the FE from theta self-duality/Poisson ("Tate's and Hecke's derivation, realized as the carrier's own
  self-duality"); thm:carrierreflection's proof (line 1523) says "No lattice and no Poisson summation enter — the classical theta identity …
  is the 1D readout shadow of J." I understand the intended hierarchy (J is the geometry, Poisson its 1D shadow), but as written the two
  passages contradict. One sentence reconciling them would do.

